She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Underneath, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Are you reviving an old memory?" asked Ivory, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari outside, as he considered her a "blemish." She was born deaf and was the only daughter of the family; all her siblings were boys.
Something similar applied to Ivory as well. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as though the world was changing too. As punishment for this difference, Ivory was given tasks that required spending most of the time alone.
In addition, Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't bother Ivory much because Ivory gained a friend.
"Ivy, you're having a birthday soon, right?" Ivory asked as she remembered that the princess had a birthday in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad flicker in her bright blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate your birthday?" asked Ivory, thinking back to the last time the princess had answered this question.
"No," knocked Kari. Ivory knew this was a difficult subject for her. Her birthday was the day she had been locked in this room and her mother banished. Ivory had been a baby at the time, but she remembered how upset the servants and the city's inhabitants had been. Ivory had heard that Eirwen had been a popular queen, and strangely enough, she could also predict things that then actually came true.
"Well, what would you like to do?" asked Ivory. Kari looked at Ivory excitedly. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm Canvas
White, various blue shades
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
"Am I supposed to get you these things?" Ivory asked the silent princess, whose braids swung back and forth from her vigorous tapping. "Yes?" Ivory giggled softly. The usually reserved princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! See you later?" asked Ivory, stood up, and slithered through the chaos of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her bedsheet.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess had finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, like malachite.
Ivory ran through the hallways again and tried to ignore the whispers of the servants.
"I've heard that she is supposed to be possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going into this room again and again."
"I've heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, that's not normal, is it?"
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn't ignore the chatter, and continued on. The king's painter's room was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was as intricately decorated as Karis' door. On it was depicted the White Dragon, one of the six original dragons said to have supposedly created Frostfell. For a history-loving painter, the image of the White Dragon on the door certainly made sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual mess. Paint splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered throughout the room, easels covering every square centimeter of the walls. Unexpectedly, however, a different sight greeted her. The entire room was clean, and against a backdrop of red velvet stood a chair. Sitting on the chair was Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being portrayed.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch how your future king is portrayed?" asked Aquilo and winked at Ivory.
"Sorry, little prince," said Ivory, largely ignoring him and gathering the things the silent princess wanted. "I'm only here to get the stuff for Mal."
"Is my little girl already wanting to go?" asked Aquilo. "But I want you to stay!"
"I, however, am not." Ivory found the art supplies on the list and put them in a box. "Besides, I'm not a girl."
However, the prince had a different opinion. "Oh sweetie, that's just a phase! As you get older, you'll grow out of it!" he said, mumbling.
"I have to go," said Ivory, feeling uneasy with the prince's response. At that moment, all the ugly remarks he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came to mind. I just want to get away from here.
"You're already leaving?" Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
"That's no behavior for a future king!" said Ivory.
"Nobody will find out. People won't believe you, and the painter will keep quiet if his life is worth anything to him." He glanced briefly at the painter and then leaned closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?" Ivory had been harassed several times in the past, but never by a prince, and certainly not by the crown prince.
"Do you actually know what the word 'No' means?" Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away from herself.
"No," answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have whatever he wants, does not know what the word "no" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why do you want to go out with someone like me? You must have around 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which swirled around in the cold air.
"Now get it through your head! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen," Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced Ivory to look at him.
